title: Maria trying to knick asian babies again
Civic Virtue by Frederick MacMonnies
description:
Civic Virtue by Frederick MacMonnies 

This marble fountain, which stands more than 20 feet high, depicts a male figure standing over two prone female figures, and was designed by sculptor Frederick MacMonnies (1863-1937) and carved by the Bronx?s Piccirilli Brothers. Although MacMonnies vehemently maintained that the piece is allegorical, from its unveiling in 1922 the fountain has been protested by people opposed to its literal and, some would say, violent imagery..
.
The funding for the sculpture materialized in 1891, following the death of New York resident Angelina Crane, who bequeathed money to the City to build a drinking fountain in her memory. After many delays, in 1909 the City commissioned MacMonnies to sculpt the fountain. MacMonnies did not finish final plans for the piece until 1919 and by the time the fountain was unveiled in 1922 in Manhattan's City Hall Park, the social climate in America had changed drastically. The 19th Amendment provided for woman suffrage, and gender issues were at the forefront of public discourse. Suffice to say, MacMonnies' brutal portrayal of Justice looking beyond the temptations of trampled female figures of vice was enough to set off a firestorm of dissent surrounding the sculpture..
.
For his part, MacMonnies insisted that portraying vice as female was in line with the allegorical representations of the day; others argued that the depiction was outdated and ultimately misogynistic. In 1941 Parks moved the statue from City Hall to its current location beside Queens Borough Hall. Standing at the corner of Queens Boulevard and Union Turnpike, it greets visitors to Queens's seat of government and justice.     

Location: Beside Queens Borough Hall; Queens Boulevard and Union Turnpike.
Sculptor: Frederick William MacMonnies.
Architect: Thomas Hastings.
Description: Male figure (heroic scale) standing over two prone female semi-figures on base inside fountain basin with four dolphin-head spouts below.
Materials:. White Georgia marble.
Dimensions: Total H: 22'10" W: 5'7"; Basin diameter: 38'.
Cast: ca. 1922.
Dedicated: 1922, 1941.
Fabricator: Piccirilli Brothers.
Donor: Bequest of Angelina Crane.
Inscription: THIS FOUNTAIN WAS ERECTED.
BY THE CITY OF NEW YORK.
WITH FUNDS BEQUEATHED BY.
MRS. ANGELINA CRANE.

title: 1971 Ford XY Falcon GTHO Phase 3 Sedan
description:
Track Red. 
Built from Oct 70-March 72
A facelift of the XW with new divided grille and revised tail lights. The GT, now with 'shaker' protruding through the centre of the bonnet, it was attached to the air cleaner and shook when the engine was running. Mechanically the XY was very similar to the XW 
An HO version was also available, with front spoiler, the old Phase 2 engine was carried over from the XW which had 750 cfm carb, solid camshaft & lifters, bigger pushrods
From May 1971 to Nov 1971, 300 Phase 3 GTHOs were made, they got the rear boot spoiler, also extractors, 780cfm carb, a revised camshaft and harmonic balancer producing 380bhp, 3 diff ratios were available to choose from. 
This car has the Globe alloys, that were offered to all Phase 3 owners, the wheels were destined for the XA Phase 4, but after the Phase 4 was canned, they needed the wheels to be homologated for Bathurst in 1972.  
The Phase 3 GTHO was the fastest 4 door car in the world and  is one of the most collectible Australian cars today.
Allan Moffat won the Hardie Ferodo 500 again in 1971, this time in a XY GTHO Phase III.
Engine; 351 Cleveland
164 GTs and GTHOs made in Track Red
Total of 1557 GTs and 300 GTHOs made

title: ARRA Supai Camp- Rehab Existing sheetrock-don
description:
Project: Rehabilitate Four Historic and Two Non-Historic Structures at Supai Camp.
.
Project overview: This project involves repairing and rehabilitating five housing units and one outbuilding that already exist at Supai Camp. Repairs will include a complete renovation of the four historic structures. This renovation work will include installing plumbing (running water and sewer), replacing roofing and windows, repainting, and upgrading the interior walls for all units. Residential fire sprinkler systems will also be installed in each of the units. Minor rehab work on the non-historic residence and common bath/laundry facility will include fixture replacement, lighting retrofit, and installation of fire sprinkler systems. Incidental site work includes the replacement of the potable water main to meet fire flow requirements and the installation of a sewer line and lift station.These repairs will vastly improve housing units and living conditions for the members of the Havasupai Tribe that reside at Supai Camp..
.
Project leader: Phil Fessler.
.
Park contact: Maureen Oltrogge, Public Affairs Officer, (928) 638-7779.
.
Project timing: This project will get under way following completion of the other ARRA project at Supai Camp, Repair and Rehabilitate Housing at Supai Camp. This will allow current residents a transition period to move from their existing, outdated housing units to the newly constructed housing units..
.
ARRA funding: $468,000.
.
Partners: Havasupai Indian Tribe.
.
Accepting outside solicitations: This project was awarded to Nagaki Design Build Associates, Phoenix, Arizona

title: Sidewalk vendor Bindia on Janpath, New Delhi 2011
description: New Delhi, India.  February, 2011.  Bindia is the  third generation of  an extended family of sidewalk vendors who work a stretch of sidewalk on the Janpath near Connaught Circle.  Generally thought of as roaming pests, sidewalk vendors often sell a specific product on a specific block their entire lifetime and pass it down to the next generation.  Several members of Bindia's extended family commute up to an hour a day to central Delhi, where each hawks a particular line of goods -- beads, leather, carved wood -- all day to tourists.  they look out for each other, and if capable enough are hired by one of the shops along the row.

title: Castlefest 2010
description: Castlefest is a festival to honour the sun, which at the Celts was worshipped as the god Lugh. This god brought mankind a lot of good things; he taught us how to grow grain and he warms the earth, so that the grain can grow and we can eat. The old Celtic harvest feast Lughnasadh is held in honour of this god. To this day heathens and Celtics alike celebrate this feast yearly around the first of August, also on Castlefest! Castlefest is een festival ter ere van de zon, die bij de Kelten werd vereerd als de god Lugh. Deze god bracht de mensen veel goede dingen. Zo leerde hij ons om graan te verbouwen en hij verwarmt de aarde, zodat het graan kan rijpen en wij te eten hebben. Het oude Keltische oogstfeest Lughnasadh is aan deze god gewijd. Tot op de dag van vandaag vieren heidenen en kelten dit feest ieder jaar rond begin Augustus, ook op Castlefest! www.castlefest.nl/

title: Trittiford Mill Pool - Yardley Wood - horse trailer
description:
A Christmas Day morning walk around the Trittiford Mill Pool in Yardley Wood. It is now part of The Shire Country Park.

From Highfield Road, down Priory Road up to Scribers Lane in Yardley Wood.

It has been parkland since the area was built up in the 1920's. The pool is fed by a millrace cut from the River Cole approx 20 yards south of Slade Lane.

There had been a mill here since at least 1779. The mill stood at the foot of Trittiford Road where the buildings at Mill Gardens can now be seen.

The mill was demolished in 1926 after a fire.

Saw a pair of horse trailers on the other side of the river!

title: Size: actual.
description:
In the front you find a model of the jewel of the Swedish Navy in the 17th century: the Vasa. 
What sets this museum apart from other naval museums is that the thing behind the model is the ACTUAL Vasa. Fresh from 1628, so to speak. 
When it was build, it  had more canons than all ships of the hostile Polish navy combined. To bad only that, while the Swedish King  Gustavus Adolphus was alright at ordering a ship with two rows of canons, his shipbuilder Henrik Hybertsson wasn't too awesome in building one.
The whole thing was very top-heavy and turned upside down after the first 20 minutes of it's maiden journey. 
There is a lesson in there somewhere.

title: St Annes Catholic Church, Underwood Road
description: St Anne's Catholic Church (and its attendant Church House on the left), was built in 1855 by Gilbert Blount. It catered for the large numbers of Irish immigrants who were settling in the area. Today , as well as its own congregation the Church is home to Brazilian worshippers, for whom services are conducted in Portuguese.
